[2] South Korea tracking cell phones - media report
Date: 7 Jun 2015
Source: Reuters [edited]
http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/07/health-mers-southkorea-idUSL3N0YS0AU20150607


S. Korea to track cellphones to prevent MERS spread; 5th person dies
- Total cases in outbreak rise to 64
- Over 2000 under quarantine, including entire village
- Health facilities with infections identified
- No need for supplementary budget for now, deputy PM says
------------------------------------------
South Korean authorities will track the cellphones of hundreds of people under quarantine to prevent the spread of Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) and reported a 5th death in the outbreak, with the number of infections rising to 64.

The government, criticised over its lack of transparency in handling the outbreak, bowed to public pressure on Sunday [7 Jun 2015] and identified 24 health facilities where infections took place or MERS patients visited.

It reported 14 confirmed new cases of MERS, adding to the largest number outside of the Middle East.

"Please understand this is an unavoidable measure for the sake of our neighbours and families," Deputy Prime Minister Choi Kyung-hwan told a news briefing in the central city of Sejong, where he announced the plan to track the mobile phones of people under quarantine to ensure they stay at home.

Over 2300 people in South Korea were under quarantine as of Sunday [7 Jun 2015], some in health care facilities but most at home, including an entire village of about 105 people in the southwest after a resident who visited a hospital where the country's 1st patient with MERS was treated turned out to be infected.

Late last month [May 2015], a South Korean man broke a voluntary house quarantine and flew to Hong Kong and then travelled to mainland China, where he tested positive for MERS.

South Korea's outbreak of the often-deadly MERS virus, 1st reported on [20 May 2015], has prompted fear and the closure last week of more than 1000 schools, with thousands of tourists cancelling plans to visit the country.

Seoul's 2 wealthy Seocho and Gangnam districts, which include a hospital where the 2nd-most MERS cases in the country occurred, will close kindergartens and schools, about 120 in total, until Wednesday [10 Jun 2015], a Seoul education official said.

"We can absolutely control this because all MERS cases in our country are infections in health facilities, not spreading into communities," Choi said.

1st identified in humans in 2012, MERS is caused by a coronavirus from the same family as the one that triggered severe acute respiratory syndrome. But MERS has a much higher death rate at 38 percent, according to World Health Organization figures.

Choi, who is also the country's finance minister, said there was no need for a supplementary budget to help the country's economy weather the outbreak. With the economy already flagging, the MERS outbreak is adding pressure for another interest rate cut, possibly as soon as the central bank's next policy meeting on [11 Jun 2015].

The latest fatality was a 75-year-old man who had been in the same Seoul hospital emergency room where a total of 17 people, including 2 medical staff, are believed to have been infected with MERS, South Korea's health ministry said.

The WHO said on Friday [5 Jun 2015] there was no evidence to suggest sustained human-to-human transmission in the community.

"Even if this arrives in communities, it's very unlikely to become pandemic," said Eom Joong-sik, professor of infectious diseases at Hallym University. "If we prevent transmissions between hospitals, we will see only episodic cases from now on."

Stephen Morse, professor of epidemiology at Columbia University, added that measures being taken such as isolating suspected cases and monitoring those in contact with patients should stop the outbreak.

"There will be a time lag, since the disease takes some days to develop, but if the proper measures are being taken, there should soon be a large falloff in the number of new cases," he said.

Health experts say the worst-case scenario is that the virus changes and spreads rapidly, as SARS did in 2002-2003, when it killed about 800 people around the world.

[Byline: Ju-min Park and Tony Munroe, additional reporting by Choonsik Yoo, Jack Kim, Sohee Kim]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The tracking of cellphones to monitor adherence to quarantine is an interesting strategy, but if people want to get around that, they just leave their cell phones at home when they go out. It will be interesting to see an evaluation of that strategy when data become available.

Noteworthy in the above media report is the mention that 24 health facilities have had MERS-CoV infected individuals attend their facilities thus far. A sizeable number, but at present it appears as though transmission has occurred in at least 4 health facilities (hospitals B, D, E and F), with 2 representing the greatest majority of cases: St Mary's in Pyeongtaek (hospital B) with 37 cases and Samsung in Seoul (hospital D) with 34 cases, accounting for 71 of the 87 cases reported as of today, 7 Jun 2015 (http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323126).

A map of South Korea showing provinces is available at http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm. - Mod.MPP]

